LOOP PIPELINE — HOW WALKS USE LOOPS
========================================

The foundational primitive. Everything above loops depends on this.

Loop empty check (~4 bonds):

  read(loop + WCURSOR)      → pipeline = write_cursor
  write(stash, pipeline)     → save write_cursor (temp)
  read(loop + SCRATCHA)      → pipeline = reader's own cursor
  test(pipeline, stash)      → 1 if equal (empty), 0 if has data

Loop read — zero-copy (~6 bonds):

  read(loop + reader_cursor)  → pipeline = reader's cursor
  AND(pipeline, mask)         → slot index
  atom TD(pipeline, recsz)    → byte offset (slot × record_size)
  add(buf_addr, pipeline)     → slot address (POINTER to record)
  — pipeline is now a pointer to the data. do NOT copy. —
  increment(reader_cursor)    → advance cursor
  write(reader_cursor_addr)   → store advanced cursor

  Consumer reads fields at offsets from the pipeline pointer.
  Record size doesn't matter. 8 bytes, 32 bytes, 64 bytes —
  same read bond, same 6 steps. The topology determines what
  the consumer reads from the pointer, not the read primitive.

  Old model: read copied data into pipeline, needed temp storage
  (stash) to save data while advancing cursor. New model: pipeline
  holds a pointer. No copy. No temp. No stash.

  This follows from boson semantics: observation doesn't move
  data. The cache hierarchy provides duplication for free.

Loop write (~6 bonds, symmetric): compute write slot from WCURSOR,
write fields to slot at offsets, advance WCURSOR.

Reader's cursor lives in per-core storage (indexed by APIC ID),
not in the loop header. Multiple readers each have their own cursor
in their own memory. Writer's cursor lives in header [0:7].
No shared mutable state. No atomics. No locks.

No global stash. Walks use per-loop scratch or per-core storage.
Global mutable state = Pauli violation (two cores writing same
address). If a walk needs temp, it owns a specific address.


